ier, we were allowed to go onto the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12417800\charrsid15356049 We}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049 st }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12417800\charrsid15356049 P}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049 ier, but not actually down below the breakwater, do you know anything of Newhaven?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid655475 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049 So it was very different from home, you wouldn't call on people like that when you were at home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2697502 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049 Oh no, it was - it was the only - taste that I had in childhood of community life.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid655475 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049 When you were small did you play with other children at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2697502 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049 At Hawley - I believe I 
learnt skipping. But there were no physical - there was no physical training of any sort in those days. There was - a ten minutes of - recreation time in the morning. In the school, yes. But -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid655475 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049 But did you have other children at home in the garden?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2697502 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049 
We were allowed to - or perhaps - my mother turned a blind eye to it, she wouldn't have approved - to - that - particularly my brother used to bring in - some of his friends, I remember having a great idea - to build a - a cottage at the bottom of the g
arden, there was a - at the bottom of the garden there was - a grassy space where I thought - it would be nice to have a cottage and live there, apart from the others. I always had an idea of being a hermit. And - so - I asked my brothers to - get their f
r
iends to help them in building a little cottage, I was - I had no doubt that I could build a cottage. The ground was dreadful, it was - there were just a few inches of soil, I remember this quite well, and underneath hard conglomerate, which was very disa
p
pointing to my father who'd wanted to make a garden. The conglomerate had been dug out to some considerable extent and piled at the bottom of the garden. So I saw this conglomerate as the walls of the cottage, I know I've seen - it's quite likely that I'd
 seen pictures of Scottish crofters. So - we got as far as - as laying - I think it was four - of these - the walls arose to the extent of about four feet I should think before the plan was discovered.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid655475 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049 What happened then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2697502 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049 It was very disappointin
g. Well my father told - told me to - put the conglomerate back where it had been. And - I know I was very disappointed. I was very disappointed because - I felt sure I could build that cottage. But my father wouldn't believe me and it - it - it seemed si
lly to him, and the fact that it was silly to him was a great disappointment to me. It - it was a blow to my self respect.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid655475 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049 Were you allowed to go out of the garden to play?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2697502 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049 No. Hopscotch on the pavement was strictly forbidden. With the other chi
ldren, yes. I remember having one friend or one associate, she was never}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12417800\charrsid15356049  an }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049 
intimate friend - at school. No, I don't think she did come to school, I can't remember her at school, but - she used to come - she used to be - allowed to come and play with me so
metimes in the garden. But - she was only happy when she was proposing some - almost impossible adventure. The sort of thing she - she - its very curious but I - I think children have those sort of compulsions. 'Cos I remember - when - I went to the - to 
V
ale Towers at the Tunbridge Wells school it was about two miles walk and - we - there were two other girls who went with me, we had a whole code of regulations in respect of this walk. And odd things you had to do, touch the pavement at one place and - an
d - on - no account step on a line between two - between - }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9663077\charrsid15356049 concreted}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049  blocks, you know. That }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid12417800\charrsid15356049 was a}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15356049  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049 thing I suppose I played a bit further up.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid655475 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049 If you did something that your parents disapproved of what would they do?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2697502 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049 Scold. My mother was good at sc
olding. My father never scolded. No. I only remember - I - I was - I was never punished in - in any other way. No. It was- I suppose it was sufficiently impressive. I remember my brother being - only on one occasion - my father punishing my brother with t
he cane. And that was a terrible occasion.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid655475 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049 What had he done?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2697502 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049 Used bad language. He took him apart and gave him a good swish. Only that once.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid655475 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049 What sort of a person do you feel your parents wanted you to grow up to be?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2697502 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049 Oh from the beginn
ing I was - I was expected to be a teacher. There was nothing else I was fit for. But - the - the occupations possible you see to young women then were very limited.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid655475 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049 Do you think you got your ideas about life more from your mother or your father?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2697502 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049 
Such ideas as I held up to the time I was adolescent I think I got from both of them. But my father was the - my father had the - the greater influence. My mother - I had to excuse my mother various things and - but I never had to excuse my father anythi
ng.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid655475 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049 If you were worried about something which of them would you go to?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2697502 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049 
I think both. I remember - when we were still at Tunbridge Wells, I must have been about six or seven perhaps - there were two boys living in the house next door - who called
 me to come and see the execution. And they - they got a frog. And - in front of me - they slit the frog open. I remember rushing indoors and - and demanding that my father should go and kill those boys.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid655475 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049 When you were younger you had a maid, was she an influence on you at all, or was that when you were too young?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2697502 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049 
Well she came from Suffolk actually. My mother - the - the maid who stayed five years, yes, she was - she was the daughter of - a Suffolk farm - a Suffolk farm labourer who had}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12417800\charrsid15356049 , }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049 I think}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12417800\charrsid15356049 ,}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049 
 fifteen shillings a week. Not she, her father. Had fifteen shillings a week to bring up - quite a large family.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid655475 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049 Did she look after you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2697502 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049 Oh yes, y-s, yes. She - she used to - take us our daily walk. My - my brother in the pram, the two younger 
were - they were - one was three years younger than me and one was six years younger than me. But -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid655475 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049 In the evening who would put you to bed?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2697502 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049 I think she did as a rule. Yes. But we were bathed downstairs by the - in a tin bath downstairs by the k
itchen fire. There were no bathrooms. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid655475 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049 Were you fond of the maid or not?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2697502 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049 Not at all. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid655475 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049 Why do you think that was?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2697502 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049 Something about her that I - I didn't like her tightness, she always wore a - a long black dress - which was button
ed down the front, and you could see her shape very much. And it was that tightness that - and - and her hair was also very tight - the - the - it was Emily's tightness that I didn't like.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid655475 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049 When you had the maid how much would you see of your mother and father?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2697502 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049 Oh they were there all the time.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid655475 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049 Your father was in the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2697502 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049 
My father - my father had a shop. A store and - he was - he was at home you see. The shop was in front of the house and - and the house was over the shop and - so that he was - he was on hand most of the time.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid655475 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049 What kind of a shop was it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2697502 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049 
Grocers. Yes, my father failed in business when - just after we came to South Norwood. He - he - he was not a business man, he ought never to have - he - he would have done 
- he had much happier and more fruitful life if he'd been a librarian or some - I remember his telling me, one shop - this was - this was at Hastings where I was born - so I don't remember this happening but - it was a new shop which he'd taken in the hop
e of - doing well there. But - it didn't do well }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12417800\charrsid15356049 and}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049 
 they - he used to - read Gibbon - when facing the customers. Yes, so it was a certain amount - a certain degree of pride, he got all through Gibbon.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid655475 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049 You had a shop in Hawley too then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2697502 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid655475 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049 What did he do after he gave up being a grocer?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2697502 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049 He took a - the - I think it's the last refuge of the broken down businessman}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid12417800\charrsid15356049 ,}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049  insurance isn't it. He went into insurance - connection.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid655475 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049 When you had the maid did you eat with her or with your parents?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2697502 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049 Oh yes, yes. She - we had a single table, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid655475 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049 A sort of nursery you mean?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2697502 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049 
We had no - we had no separate nursery. No. The - there was the dining room and the - what was called the sitting room, not the drawing room, the sitting room
. And - and the bedrooms and there was a big storeroom at the top of the house. I would - comparatively recently I went to }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9663077\charrsid15356049 Tunbridge}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049  Wells to see if that - if that store was still there. Oh yes, it is and it's still a grocers shop. Especially after all that time.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid655475 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049 How many bedrooms were there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2697502 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049 Four.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid655475 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049 When you were older then you ate with your parents?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2697502 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049 We always did. We always had - we always had a common table.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid655475 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049 With the maid sitting there with the family?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2697502 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid655475 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049 Were your parents strict about table manners or not?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2697502 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049 Oh yes, oh yes, we were taught table manners. I don't know, }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9663077\charrsid15356049 I've}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049  probably forgotten them now.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid655475 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049 What sort of things did they insist on then? Were you allowed to talk at table?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2697502 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid655475 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049 Could you bring toys to the table?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2697502 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049 No. Not toys nor books - not - not when the meal was set you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid655475 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049 Were you made to finish everything or could you leave something if you didn't like it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2697502 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049 I don't think there was any compulsion to finish. But the number of slices of bread and butter were limited to four.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid655475 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049 Why was that do you think?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2697502 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049 At breakfast or tea.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid655475 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049 Did they disapprove of bread and butter?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2697502 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049 No, I think it was because - my mother considered that was sufficient for anybody -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid655475 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049 Could you ask for more or other things though?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2697502 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049 
Second helpings, yes, you could - you were allowed a second helping at - in fact you were expected to have second helping at - midday dinner. But I don't think we had anything after tea - I can't remember 
that there was any supper meal. Not for the children, we were put to bed - fairly early.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid655475 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049 What would the typical day's menu be, what would you have at breakfast?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2697502 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049 Porridge or hominy. Bread and butter and jam.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid655475 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049 And midday?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2697502 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049 Midday - well it would depend upon the time of }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9663077\charrsid15356049 the week}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049 
. There was always a joint on Saturday. It was a day for a hot meal on Saturday. Joint with all the accessories on Saturday. My mother had - she told me this - she'd agreed with my father before she married him that 
he would never require a hot meal on Sunday. So that it was always cold on Sundays, it was the - the joint was large enough you see to be carved cold on Sunday but - there were always vegetables cooked on Sunday and there was - generally a fruit tart. Som
e
thing of that sort, that; could be - was generally prepared on Saturday you see as well. And - and then on Monday - that was also a cold meat day. The next day - I think we - it - the meals varied the first of the week you see. I might - it might be meat 
pudding, it might - it was never fish and chips.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid655475 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049 Did you have soups?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2697502 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049 Soup? Not much soup, no. No - soup was very little - seemed to be very little used in - in that -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid655475 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049 You were at school in Croydon?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2697502 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049 Yes, I was in school - in Croydon from }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14095999\charrsid15356049 1892}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049  to }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14095999\charrsid15356049 1}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049 
896. That was a - that was what was still called a board school, actually at - at the time it was being taken over by the local public authority you see, rather than - I think - I can't- you probably know better than I do - when the board schoo
ls - ceased and - and the councils took over. 1902-'03, was it as late as that? Oh yes. Yes. Oh yes. Oh well, then it was - it was actually a board school at that time.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid655475 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049 Did you go on to be a pupil teacher?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2697502 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid655475 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049 At the same school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2697502 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049 The
 - it happened that I - that I was at the same school but I - I had no actual teaching in the school because - they were - there had been established - I can't say what year - a pupil teachers centre, for the whole of Croydon you see. So that - so I - I -
 my st}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14095999\charrsid15356049 udies were at the pupil teacher centre}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049 
 for four - I was apprenticed for four years. But that was - not when I was fourteen. 'Cos - everybody expected me to be a teacher, she wasn't fit for anything else. And - I was quite prepared to be a teacher, onl
y - I hated Croydon. We'd come from - from - Hawley in Surrey which was then just a village and I loved the country and I hated the town. And - at fourteen when I should have taken the entrance examination - I - I said I wasn't - I wasn't going to pledge 
m
yself to stay another four years in town. So - my parents sighed and left the matter to me. I wasted nearly two years. I - oh there - I was doing a lot of petty writing, I was writing from the time I was - eight. And - I had - probably - castles in the ai
r because a poem or something would be accepted by one paper or another you know. Of course I was - I was going straight into authorship and that would be that. No need for any }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9663077\charrsid15356049 
school teaching}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049 . Well I wasted about eighteen months I suppose and there then I found I was actually in a dead end.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid655475 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049 Did you take jobs during those eighteen months?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2697502 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049 
I - went to a - a sub-post office where there was less post office work than selling cheap magazines and that sort of thing. But - then I happened, quite by acci
dent, to meet my old teacher and - I told her what the situation was and she said, well, it isn't too late, why not take the - the next examination? Which I did. But it - you see, it made me - so much later in getting my full certificate.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid655475 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049 So you came back to Croydon to do that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2697502 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049 I hadn't gone away.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid655475 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049 You'd been working in the Post Office?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2697502 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049 Oh the Post Office was - yes, this was in Croydon.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid655475 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049 Can you tell me anything about what it was like being a pupil teacher?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2697502 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049 D.H. Lawrence was 
also a pupil teacher. Everybody knows about D.H. Lawrence and I don't propose to say anything more about him but - it - it - it just happened that his course of education is very much the same as mine. He won a scholarship to Grammar School. And he - from
 
the Grammar School - he went to a pupil teacher centre, and - worked there for two years. In my case it was four years. The apprenticeship was four years. And - we - the - the students - were - the - the younger ones, the two younger - younger years were 
t
here - all the - the afternoons and only went to - to school for school practice in the mornings. Later on you went only three afternoons in the week, and you taught the rest of the time you see. And the closing of the - the final exam which decided wheth
e
r or not you were - would be accepted in college, not the university of course, not. The sort of cheap institution that I believe is described very well indeed in Hardy's Jude the Obscure, do you know Jude the Obscure. Well Jude the Obscure made me decide
 I would never go to a college.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid655475 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049 So you didn't go to a training college at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2697502 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049 I didn't - I never - no, I - I didn't go to a training college.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid655475 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049 Just your four years as a pupil teacher and then you start teaching?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2697502 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049 Well started - then I s
tarted teaching full time - but - studying at night you see, and I had - I also had Polytechnic classes and - that was for another two years. And then I took the actual teachers certificate.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid655475 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049 Did you teach in Croydon then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2697502 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049 Yes, oh I taught in Croydon for many years. I came here.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid655475 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049 Were you still living at home then, all that time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2697502 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049 Not all the time. Until - 1917. No, 1915. 'Til 1915 I was living at home.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid655475 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049 Was social life very different once you'd started working?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2697502 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049 I don't think t
here was very much difference. Not very much difference. Of course, round about that time - we had the first cinemas. There was one - not very far from my home. But - you didn't go to places like that. They were cheap and nasty. They were }{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9663077\charrsid15356049 intended}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049  for the people of Wentworth Road}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14095999\charrsid15356049  w}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049 hich was one of Croydon's slums.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid655475 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049 Were you allowed to go out to the theatre, your parents didn't mind so much what you did by that stage?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2697502 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049 Are you thinking of the parents?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid655475 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049 Did your parents mind what you did in the evenings at all by that time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2697502 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049 
Well you see - the evenings in those days were not as attractive as the evenings nowadays. And you didn't want to go out, there was nothing to go out for. Unless you were connected with - one of the religious organizations
 and there was a Band of Hope or a - I've forgotten what the other organization was but - nearly it was - nearly - nearly every non-conformist church had some kind of social organization. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7633170\charrsid15356049 
But that - that didn't mean - a club or anything of that kind. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049 You w
ent occasionally to - some particular concerts or a particular lecture, but- it - it wasn't a place you could go to at - any evening. Nothing in the nature of - of youth clubs. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid655475 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049 Would you have friends come to the home at that time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2697502 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049 I suppose some people did. But - I wasn't - I - I wasn't at all - swift to make friends.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid655475 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049 So it was very much like you were describing earlier on?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2697502 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid655475 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049 Did you take an interest in politics at that time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2697502 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049 Not in the least.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid655475 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049 You didn't have a vote?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2697502 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049 
I think my first - my first interest - the first time I took any interest in politics was - the - at the time of the - election of 1905 when - the Lib - the - the Conservatives had had a long run and - the Liberals got in. Now my father was a - 
definitely a Liberal. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7633170\charrsid15356049 
He was never an active politician, he - the last thing he would have done would have been to have gone to public meetings or anything of that kind, but - his opinions, he'd - he'd read quite a lot and - and - he was certainly very much Liberal. }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049 
And this - he was so enthusiastic about the result of this - this - election that - I began to think there -might be something in it. I wasn't - he - he was - he was hoping all sorts of things, for all sorts of reforms - and that had been promis
ed by the Liberals you see. But - I was much more s}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14095999\charrsid15356049 c}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049 
eptical and - only gave very little attention to it, I did just know later on that - Lloyd George had instituted a - an old age pension, that seemed to me a ra}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14095999\charrsid15356049 
ther wonderful thing and - but I}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049  suppose it w
asn't until - I was about - I suppose it was a - would have been about 1916 - when I came in contact with - with a woman, she was a retired London headmistress who played the harp. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7633170\charrsid15356049 
I was very interested in - in violin playing at the time and - I had a friend who was - also played the violin and - we two used to go and play with this harpist. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049 
She had a nice flat in Sydenham. And she }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14095999\charrsid15356049 was}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049 
 a Fabian. And - she - brought me into the Fabian fold. So I used to go after that to - I went to several of the Fabian summer schools. Do you know }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14095999\charrsid15356049 the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049 Fabian }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14095999\charrsid15356049 S}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049 ociety.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid655475 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049 Did you support the suffragettes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2697502 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049 
I did not. I - I couldn't understand how women - could so lose their dignity as to behave as the suffragettes did. It - and it - nor did it ever seem to me that - tha
t the vote - although I - I - regarded it as being a - an act of injustice that women were not - hadn't the vote, but - it didn't seem worth what they put in - in - into the suffragette movement. Of course I was quite young then, but that was the impressi
ons I had.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid655475 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049 Did you carry on attending church at this stage or did you lose interest in church?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2697502 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049 
Well - my parents were both Congregationalists. But I was never associated - with - not during my childhood, with - with any particular church, I was sent to Sunday school. It ended there. I - I was never made a member of - of any church. }{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7633170\charrsid15356049 Indeed - my - father objected to my being christened because he considered that - that a person should be of age to form judgments before - he - he didn't like - they d
id promise - they did promise and vow three things in my name and that sort - so as it runs in the - in the catechism. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049 
So that I was - was not christened. None of us were christened. And therefore you see I'm entirely unregenerate.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid655475 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7633170\charrsid15356049 What would a typical Sunday be like in about 1910, what sort of things would you do, do you think?}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2697502 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049 
1910? Well - you could - I - I'm thinking of being in Croydon then you see. I was still living in my parents - home. And - I might - with a friend who was - a member - oh
 yes, I did belong at that time to a - the choir of a Congregational church in Croydon which had the - Countess of Huntingdon connection and used the - the church }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7633170\charrsid15356049 liturgy}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049  with deletions and - we had - we had a very good choir, we did - a lot of - oratorio 
work in that church. It was because of the music that I was there you see. And - that - that was - that would have been my Sunday morning in - and possibly, but not always, Sunday evening. And - then in the afternoon - probably I would be studying somethi
ng or other. Or else - the - Henry Wood concerts - were Sat - on the Saturday - it - that was rather on a Saturday afternoon my musical friend and I would go to the - one of the symphony concerts at }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid14095999\charrsid15356049 Queen\rquote s}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049  Hall. But - you couldn't get anything to eat on Sunday if you went to the - to London.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid655475 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049 Did you go bicycling?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2697502 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049 
No, I - I - no, I didn't learn to cycle until I was - past thirty. No, my mother didn't - my mother had no liking for bicycles, she didn't like my father's bicycle. He - he was quite a 
pioneer, he used to ride a penny farthing bicycle when I was quite - when I was - a small child but my mother didn't like it. And- particularly when he - rode to London to the - celebrated preacher, on his penny farthing bicycle. She thought that was a ve
ry risky thing to do.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid655475 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049 You told me that your father took you through the poor parts on the way to the Tate Gallery?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2697502 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049 Oh yes, yes. Nine Elms.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid655475 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049 Were you brought up do you think with a fairly clear idea of the social classes of the country, what s
ort of ideas did you have at that stage about social class?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2697502 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049 
Rich and poor, I suppose I divided them - just roughly like that you see. But I don't think I analysed the reasons for wealth or poverty. No, not until - not until I got into the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7633170\charrsid15356049 Fabian}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12417800\charrsid15356049 Society}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049 .
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid655475 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049 Were you - what was the attitude your parents brought you up to have towards the poor?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2697502 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049 Well - when - an organ grinder with a }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7633170\charrsid15356049 monkey}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049  came around you threw him pennies. And that was a - that was the proper thing to do. And you also took - ill
uminated picture books to hospitals - to give to children in hospital beds. I remember doing that. I think I had, as far as I can remember, sheets of pink linen which were cut into pages and - you stuck Christmas cards or - or anything in the way of colou
red cards on them, you filled them up like that and took them to the hospital.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid655475 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049 When you were a schoolteacher how did you feel about the poor children in the class?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2697502 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049 Well I thought it was quite wrong that they should be like that. But - I - don thi
nk even then that I made any reasonable analysis as to why there was all this difference. I knew that they were poor, I knew it was because the - their parents had very little money. But - you see, I was born a poet - and so- only circumstances turned me 
into an economist and that was at rather a late date.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid655475 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049 Were you brought up to expect respect from poorer people?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2697502 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049 I - no, I don't think so. We had - I had as a child simply nothing to do with poorer people. We had a maid who was - was - I was told
 was one of - a big family of fifteen, her father being an agricultural labourer in Suffolk and - I knew that it was difficult for them to get enough to eat at home and so she had to go out into service. And I certainly felt that people who went into serv
ice were inferior people. Without thinking about it al all, they - they were - the - there was that sense of class. And I think everybody has it still. And sometimes people don't realize that they have it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid655475 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049 Were you brought up to show respect to people who were thought superior to your family?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2697502 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049 
I don't think I was brought into touch with any superiors. My - my father was - was very much an independent you see. And - he had his own business and - there was reliance - there were no reliance on - on a 
master - on the next - in fact we had nothing - practically nothing to do with any class above our own.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid655475 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049 Would you say there was a concept of a real lady which your mother would talk about at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2697502 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049 No, I don't think so. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7633170\charrsid15356049 I - I remember of course be
ing told about the Queen at the - the time of the - of - in Victoria's Jubilee and - but she was never a real person to me. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049 
When I - when I began to read novels, the people in - in the novels wee re far more real to me than - any people outside - the family. Oh yes
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid655475 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049 What about the difference between the rough and respectable poor?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2697502 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049 
I don't know whether I told you that when we were in - when I was - between seven and eight and - attending a private school on the edge of the common - I had - pretty w
ell two miles to walk and at one point there was - there were two other little girls from the neighbourhood who used to come with me and we walked and at one point we - used to run because - we were passing what my mother called the ragged school. It was 
t
he school - a school - it was a Roman Catholic school actually and I daresay a good many of them were ragged, and we were - we - this was - this was a terrifying point because - especially in the afternoons when we came back from school because just at th
a
t time the ragged school children would be coming out and they would surround us and - and jeer at us you see and the - of course we - we had to wear gloves and - and be extremely respectable. The - one of the school regulations was that you mustn't be se
en in the street without gloves.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid655475 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049 At the board school?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2697502 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049 
No, no, this wasn't a board school. Oh the - this was - this was when I was between seven and eight you see. That was in - at Tunbridge Wells. But - when we went to Hawley there was a - there
 was no school of the sort you see, there was no private school. It was my mother's great difficulty that there was no school she could send me to nearer than Redhill and Redhill was a long way away and - when there was no bus you see and - and - really n
o
 transport so - very reluctantly she let me go to the village school there. And - I suppose I got on so well at the village school and - we got to like the people there and - the teachers that is to say, I can't remember that I had anything to do with the
 children there. I used to go to school and come home, go to school and come home. It - I didn't associate with them at all. It - I wasn't - companions didn't seem to be necessary.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid655475 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049 What sort of attitudes do you think the teachers were trying to get ove
r to the children at that time, did they emphasise particularly things like tidiness and punctuality do you think?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2697502 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049 Well - the - there was an examination you know. A - a yearly - a yearly examination when the three inspectors - when three - at least t
hree inspectors came down and - and - set tests in reading, writing and arithmetic, and recorded each child's performance and according to the record - the - total record, the school grant depended. So it was - it wasn't born in upon me because I - I coul
d read before I went to school, I could read at the age of- five fairly fluently but - it was very necessary to read and write. Sovereigns and half sovereigns, carried them around in a little bag. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid7633170\charrsid15356049 The first time I went to - to Germany - my - great-aunt knit
ted me a - or crocheted me a little bag to put my sovereigns in so that I - I had - I think it was - let me see - I know the whole excursion, where a friend and I went down the Rhine as far as Ranheim by the boat, we were gone more than a week, and the wh
ole excursion cost seven pounds. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049 And I had - I had seven or eight pounds then saved them and - took them in this little bag you see. This was - before the war. This would have been 1912.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid655475 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049 That was the first time you went abroad?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2697502 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid655475 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049 Did you have a holiday every year at that time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2697502 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049 School holidays?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid655475 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049 Going away from Croydon, did you go somewhere different each year?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2697502 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049 My parents didn't. I don't remember them having a - a holiday away from home until I was pretty well grown up. But 
- I used to stay with a - a cousin at Newhaven which was my mother's home. And - summer holidays were - were generally spent there.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid655475 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049 Was that while you were teaching?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2697502 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049 No, that was while I was - when I was a child.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid655475 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049 When you were older what would you do for a holiday then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2697502 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049 
From the time I began to teach? I had a friend - she was the teacher with whom I first taught when I was sent into a - the school as a pupil teacher to teach you see, I - I was in her class and she and I became - becam
e great friends. I used to go away with her for - summer holidays and - oh I did several times. In England, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid655475 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049 To the seaside or the country?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2697502 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049 Oh yes. Well - it was seaside generally.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid655475 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049 Did you belong to a teachers union at that time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2697502 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049 
Do you think it likely? No. I was - in those days I - I had a feeling - of I still have it to some extent - that one person is very desirable - and one mouse you see, I've got a nice little mouse now in the kitchen - shows himself now and again and he's -
 he's - well I like him quite a lot, or her quite a lot. But if that mouse becomes mice - I }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7633170\charrsid15356049 shan't}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049 
 like it. I shall take other steps. But - the - I had - as I say, I had no - no desire for society, for unions and - no - no - they had no attraction for me at all. The }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7633170\charrsid15356049 Fabian}{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14095999\charrsid15356049 S}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049 ociety was the first - society of the kind which I contacted.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid655475 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049 You had this maid, do you think your mother gave her moral guidance about her way of behaving and so on?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2697502 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049 I'm quite sure she did. I think it was a - it was ultimately
, although this - this is only surmise on my part - that it was something to do with moral guidance which caused - Emily to leave.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid655475 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049 You don't remember the details now?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2697502 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049 No. No, she'd been - she'd been with us five years and - there had never been 
any - differences as far as I knew between my mother and Emily but - I was told that Emily was leaving and - }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7633170\charrsid15356049 Emily}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049 
 did a lot of weeping and my mother looked - very much distressed also and - and then Emily went home. And that was the last of Emily.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid655475 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049 Did you also have a washerwoman come in?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2697502 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049 
No, the - the - the washing was - sent to a laundry. It was probably a private laundry you see, one of the cottagers would have - yes. I was thinking of Hawley particularly.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid655475 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049 What about making and mending clothes, would you have a dressmaker to do that or was that done in the home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2697502 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049 
I think it was possible to have a dressmaker in then but we didn't. My mother knew various dressmakers and - when we wanted new clothes she - gave the order to the dressmake
r, whoever she happened to be at the time you see. It was a - it was an occupation for women who - who - were not trained in any other way and - and who - may have been quite good needlewomen. But they worked on their own, they were not employed - not emp
loyed - in - not in my area, they were not employed in - in factory work at all.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid655475 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049 Would your mother mend clothes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2697502 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049 Oh yes, she would - she - she always mended the stockings and - and - when tapes wanted s}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid14095999\charrsid15356049 e}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049 wing on and buttons and that sort of things
, she didn't - she did that kind of thing. But she was not - she was not a needlewoman. There were of course many women who - who - did very fine needlework and liked needlework and did it in their own homes but - my mother didn't care for needlework, she
 did it because she had to sometimes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid655475 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049 Did she have to do her own cooking?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2697502 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049 Oh yes, yes. Yes, she was quite a good cook.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid655475 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049 Were you expected to carry out housework tasks as a child?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2697502 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049 I remember how delighted I was - I suppose I must have been about five - when I was first allowed to take tea - }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7633170\charrsid15356049 tea cloth}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049 
 and wipe the tea things up. It was while it was - while it was a novelty you see, I liked doing that sort of thing. But - when it ceased to be a novelty I wasn't so keen. But - the - none of the rougher work was ever given to me.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid655475 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049 But did you have little regular tasks after you were five which you were expected to do?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2697502 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049 I can't remember - oh I - I think I was expected to make my own bed. And to - see that toys were put away you see and
 - I did occasionally, but I think this was very occasional, make a - a dress for a doll. But - I can't remember that I ever made anything for anybody else. We were not encouraged to make things for our relatives as some children were.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid655475 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049 Did you have hobbies as a child?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2697502 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049 I don't think so - except reading, you see, I was always reading.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid655475 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049 You didn't keep any pets?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2697502 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049 Oh my father had rabbits. Yes. Yes, he kept them - he kept them himself and - but we were very - I don't }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid14095999\charrsid15356049 know}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049  whether - whether 
they were kept because he thought it was good for the children to have animals, we - the - the rabbits - we were not allowed to play with the rabbits. We - we could feed them but - we were not allowed to have them out and handle them and - we always had a
 cat.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid655475 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049 You didn't keep hens?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2697502 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid655475 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049 You didn't eat the rabbits?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2697502 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049 Yes. Yes. I disliked that very much. That a rabbit had to be eaten.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid655475 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049 Did you grow any fresh vegetables?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2697502 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049 Well my father attempted to do so but he was very unsuccessful. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7633170\charrsid15356049 
That was at Hawley where there was a good big - it was a good big garden but the soil was very,very poor, about six inches underneath the ground I think I told you this, when I mentioned-trying to build a house at the bottom of the garden. }{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049 The - the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7633170\charrsid15356049 conglomerate}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049 
 that you had to - had to treat it with a pick to get it out at all so to - it wasn't a - it wasn't }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7633170\charrsid15356049 a productive}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049  garden at all.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid655475 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049 Was supper a big meal in your family?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2697502 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049 No, it was a very light meal. In fact, I don't think as children we we
re expected to have anything after tea. No, I can't remember any supper, not until - my - I can remember pupil - in pupil teacher days we used to - I used then when I'd finished my study for the evening you see to come and have something light to - not as
 a child.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid655475 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049 You mean just a cup of tea and some bread and jam, that kind of thing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2697502 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049 
Never - never tea. Shouldn't have slept if I - cocoa. Yes. It was generally cocoa and a - bread and butter and cheese and tomatoes as far as I can remember, that was the regulation supper.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid655475 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049 Did your mother bake her own bread?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2697502 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid655475 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049 Would she bottle fruit?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2697502 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049 
No. No. She did what was necessary. I don't think she was ever very fond of housekeeping. But what I - whatever she did she did exceedingly well. 
But she didn't take a pride in - in bottling and cake making and - and - pastry and that sort of thing as some women do.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid655475 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049 Did she make any medicines?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2697502 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049 No, she didn't make any. I always wondered where my mother got her homeopathic ideas from. 'Cou
rse it was rather early in the day, in the '80's. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7633170\charrsid15356049 
She had - the - the - little bottles of - of pills, the homeopathic ones - all of which had a poison name you see, nux vomica and - and aconite and - I can't remember them now but - we had three or four, and she had great faith in those. }{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049 
In all - if you were in the least feverish you always had aconite. But - where she got - generally speaking she was very old fashioned and she'd been brought up in an old Sussex town, you see, where - where they lived accord
ing to tradition very much. But somehow or other that homeopathic idea got in.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid655475 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049 She would call a doctor if you were ill though would she?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2697502 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049 She - she was very loathe to call a doctor. She - she considered that most childish - she - she knew how to 
deal with most childish troubles. If you had a - a - a bad cold and cough, especially if you had a cough, you had a tallow plaster on your chest. And - of course the - there was the business of chilblains - chilblains - chilblains were - I don't know whet
h
er children have chilblains now as they did then. No, they - I think the - the - the schools was frightfully draughty and - the - and the heating you see was all on one side, it was - just one big coal fire. And - there was a great deal of distinction sti
ll in school, of course that there isn't now - so that - I did suffer rather badly from chilblains but - on the feet.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid655475 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049 How did she treat those?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2697502 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049 Oh - I don't know that she treated them at all, I think they were things - they were among the things that had to be endured. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid655475 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049 Can you remember at all whether you ate any tinned food at that time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2697502 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3767260\charrsid15356049 
Towards the end of the time. I should say that - that at the beginning of this century we were having pineapple. Pineapple was the first. Yes.
